--- PART 4: GAP ANATOMY AND DISJOINTNESS MECHANISM ---
Two 3-cycles are disjoint iff their 6 vertices are distinct.
For circulant T_p, a 3-cycle at (v, v+g1, v+g1+g2) is characterized by gap triple (g1,g2,g3).
Question: which gap-triple pairs are more likely to produce disjoint cycles?

  p=7, Paley:
    Gap types: [(1, 2, 4)]
    Disjointness between gap type pairs:
      (1, 2, 4) × (1, 2, 4): disj=14/182 (7.7%)

  p=7, Interval:
    Gap types: [(1, 3, 3), (2, 2, 3)]
    Disjointness between gap type pairs:
      (1, 3, 3) × (1, 3, 3): disj=14/42 (33.3%)
      (1, 3, 3) × (2, 2, 3): disj=0/49 (0.0%)
      (2, 2, 3) × (2, 2, 3): disj=14/42 (33.3%)

  p=11, Paley:
    Gap types: [(1, 1, 9), (1, 5, 5), (3, 3, 5), (3, 4, 4)]
    Disjointness between gap type pairs:
      (1, 1, 9) × (1, 1, 9): disj=66/110 (60.0%)
      (1, 1, 9) × (1, 5, 5): disj=44/121 (36.4%)
      (1, 1, 9) × (3, 3, 5): disj=22/121 (18.2%)
      (1, 1, 9) × (3, 4, 4): disj=22/121 (18.2%)
      (1, 5, 5) × (1, 5, 5): disj=66/110 (60.0%)
      (1, 5, 5) × (3, 3, 5): disj=44/121 (36.4%)
      (1, 5, 5) × (3, 4, 4): disj=22/121 (18.2%)
      (3, 3, 5) × (3, 3, 5): disj=66/110 (60.0%)
      (3, 3, 5) × (3, 4, 4): disj=44/121 (36.4%)
      (3, 4, 4) × (3, 4, 4): disj=66/110 (60.0%)

  p=11, Interval:
    Gap types: [(1, 5, 5), (2, 4, 5), (3, 3, 5), (3, 4, 4)]
    Disjointness between gap type pairs:
      (1, 5, 5) × (1, 5, 5): disj=66/110 (60.0%)
      (1, 5, 5) × (2, 4, 5): disj=88/242 (36.4%)
      (1, 5, 5) × (3, 3, 5): disj=44/121 (36.4%)
      (1, 5, 5) × (3, 4, 4): disj=22/121 (18.2%)
