--- PART 8: WHY PALEY MAXIMIZES H AT p=3 mod 4 ---
Summary of evidence:

1. FOURIER FLATNESS: Paley QR set has perfectly flat |S_hat(t)|^2 = p for t!=0
   This gives MINIMUM additive energy E(S)
   Interval has concentrated Fourier spectrum, higher energy

2. UNIFORM CO-OCCURRENCE: In Paley T_p, every vertex pair appears in the same
   number of 3-cycles. This uniformity extends to higher cycles.
   Interval has non-uniform co-occurrence (gap d -> d shared 3-cycles).

3. RESONANCE CONSTRUCTIVE INTERFERENCE: At p=3 mod 4, ALL odd q have
   chi(q) consistent with chi(ab) in the D^{2n} Walsh decomposition.
   This means ALL resonance levels contribute the SAME sign to h_hat.

4. GAUSS SUM FACTORIZATION: D_k = sum sigma_l sin(2pi*k*l/p)
   For sigma = QR indicators, D_k ~ Im(g(k)) = chi(k)*sqrt(p)
   This gives D_k^{2n} = p^n for all k, maximizing trace contributions.

5. OCF CONNECTION: H(T) = I(Omega(T), 2) = sum alpha_j * 2^j
   Paley maximizes alpha_1 (total cycle count) while having fewer alpha_2
   (disjoint pairs). The linear term 2*alpha_1 dominates 4*alpha_2.
   More cycles with MORE overlap, each cycle contributes to H independently.
